Overview¶

Classification task and Model type¶

The importance of protein conformational space¶

Proteins express their function mainly using their 3D structures, conformations, and their movements, dynamics. The ensamble of conformations that a protein can adopt composes the conformational landscape of that protein. This conformational space is intimately linked to a protein function. Low-energy conformations shape valleys in the conformational space, this valleys are correlated with stable geometries, which nature selected to be functional (Biological processes kinda need some reliability to function). The heights of these valleys determine the ability to transition between states.

Molecular Biologists strive to obtain a representation of the conformational space, as it represents a key component to understand protein function and therefore to rationalize biology at a molecular level. Computational techniques helped the sampling of the conformational space with an ensable of techniques, many of the realm of energy minimization, such as simulated annealing, Monte Carlo simulations, bias and un-biased molecular dynamics and so on.

In simple molecular models, the choice of the feature space aka collective variables used to visualize the conformational space can be quite trivial, however for bigger and complex molecules such as proteins the choice of features used to rationalize the conformational space has a huge impact on the visualization of the conformational space and therefore in our biological interpretation of it.

Except for some studies where the choice of features is justified by pre-existing knowledge of the system, one type of feature is usually used arbitrarly (certain research groups tend to use angles, while other distances between atoms and so on). Both the domain knowledge approach and the arbitrary approach risk to hide features that are critical in shaping the conformational space and suffer from potential human bias. This problem is the elephant in the room in the molecular modeling community.

We want an un-bias method to obtain a conformational space which does not rely on our human knowledge of the system.

Some pioneering studies tried to find combination of heterogenous protein features (angles, distances ...) by processing random subsetsm picked using genetic algoriths, in a NN.

The model: multi-modal¶

Here we want to employ a multi-modal neural network where different types of protein features are used to build a conformational space. We basically want to throw all the possible features to the NN, which then will find for us the set of features that characterize the conformational space.

To do so we built a multi-modal autoencoder-like NN, where different protein features represent different modes on the network. The goal of the model is not to rebuild the feature space, but to build the 3D Cartesian conformation. The assumption is that is a model can reconstruct the protein structure from its features, it should have a good representation of the conformational space to build the structure from.

Data description¶

Collection method: Molecular Dynamics simulations¶

The data was collected by Francesco Trozzi for a research project at SMU using ManeFrame2. The data consists of Molecular Dynamics simulations, where each frame of the simulation is a different conformation of the protein. Molecular Dynamics simulations are based on Newtonian Mechanics, where the energy of a conformation determines the movement of the atoms, which will define the next conformation and so on. Thus the simulations can be interpreted as a literal movie of the protein behaviour overtime.

Importance¶

We performed several Molecular Dynamics simulations of a ACE2 protein in different conditions. ACE2 is a protein of the RAAS system (regulates blood pressure) which is used by coronaviruses to enter host cells. The simulations where performed to understad the dynamical and cnformational profile of this protein (aka rationalize the conformational space) in various condition (in presence and absence of zinc, or viral protein, from different starting conformations). It is in fact crucial not only to know which drugs bind to this protein to help us dealing with blood-pressure anomalies or covid pathologies, but to understand HOW this protein functions at a molecular level so that we can intervene more even more effectively and rationalize why certain drugs work the way they do.

Data details¶

We simulated a total of 9 microseconds, which translates to 90000 frames (aka datapoints). The simulations were performed from 2020 to 2021 in the context of a study of the dynamical behavior of the ACE2 receptor (yet to be published).

Evaluation criteria¶

To evaluate the performance of the model in building the conformational space, we evaluated how well the model can reconstruct the 3d structure of a protein given its features. The comparison between the predicted 3d structure and the correct 3d structure (3d structure classification if you will) was evaluated using Mean Squared Error (MSE). The reason for this choice is simply because MSE value can be easily interpreted as measure of difference between two structures. In fact, the Molecular Biology community mostly use RMSD (which is basically MSE) to define the magnitude of structural changes over the protein. Since in this study our data is unlabeled, the (val)loss, espressed as MSE, is going to function as our evaluation criteria.

Description of the modes¶

As we were working with raw data (collection of protein structures from trajectory "movie"), the number of modalities depended on in how many ways we wanted to featurize our protein. Therefore the data for each modality are within the same domain. In this study we used two:

  • Distances between alpha carbons (atom which resides in the backbone of the protein)
  • Dihedral angles formed by consecutives alpha carbons.

The reason for this choice is that protein conformations are characterized by secondary structures and their spacial relations (tertiary structure). On top of the distances within each secondary structure, dihedral angles should help refine the shape of this secondary structures. The angles of a helix, should be different from the ones of a sheet and so on. Dihedral angles have in fact been proposed as metric to characterize secondary structures. On the other hand, alpha carbon distances should help define the relative position between secondary structures.

# Take indices of start and end featurized trajectories
parser = argparse.ArgumentParser()
parser.add_argument("-d", "--directory", required= True, help="location of featurized trajejectories")
parser.add_argument("-i", "--trajs_indices", nargs='+', required= True, help="indices of trajectories")
args = parser.parse_args()
d = args.directory

ref = md.load(d+'/traj_0.nc', top=d+'/traj_0.prmtop')
ref_topo = ref.topology
ref_table, ref_bonds = ref_topo.to_dataframe()

#make list for consecutives alpha carbons for dihedrals
cd =[]
for i in range(589):
    tmp = [i, i+1, i+2, i+3]
    cd.append(tmp)
ll = np.array(cd)


if ref_table['resName'].iloc[0] == 'ILE':
    ref_indx = ref_topo.select('(resid 0 to 591) and (name CA)')
else:
    ref_indx = ref_topo.select('(resid 1 to 592) and (name CA)')
ref = ref.atom_slice(ref_indx)


for i in args.trajs_indices:
    traj = md.load(d+'/traj_'+i+'.nc', top=d+'/traj_'+i+'.prmtop')
    topo = traj.topology
    table, bonds = topo.to_dataframe()

    if table['resName'].iloc[0] == 'ILE':
        indx = topo.select('(resid 0 to 591) and (name CA)')
    else:
        indx = topo.select('(resid 1 to 592) and (name CA)')

    traj = traj.atom_slice(indx)
    topo = traj.topology
    table, bonds = topo.to_dataframe()
    
    # Compute distances between alpha carbons
    contact_traj, pairs = md.compute_contacts(traj, contacts='all', scheme='ca')
    
    # Compute dihedrals between consecutive alpha carbons
    dihe = md.compute_dihedrals(traj, indices=ll)
    
    # Extract coordinates for NN output
    sup_traj = traj.superpose(ref)
    sup_traj_np = sup_traj.xyz

Train/test split¶

We have a substantial amount of data, which has likely present a significant amount of redundancy. In fact, the protein spends most of the time in energy minima and the conformational changes between minima are not drastic.

For this reason we didn't believe cross validation necessary, but we opted for a less computational train/test split. For each model we used 60300 datapoints for training and validated on 29700 samples.

print('Prepare data')
def prepare_data_for_fitting(traj_n, feat):
    ftraj = {}
    for key in range(traj_n):
        value = np.load('../../../../2-featurize/'+str(key)+'_'+str(feat)+'_scaled.npy')
        ftraj[key] = value
    return ftraj

def prepare_data_reconstruct(traj_n):
    ftraj = {}
    for key in range(traj_n):
        value = np.load('../../../2-featurize/traj_sup_'+str(key)+'.npy')
        ftraj[key] = value
    return ftraj

Description of single models¶

We used two encoders/decoder models, one using only dihedral angles and one using only the pairwise distances between alpha carbons. The layers in the reconstruction part of the model (the decoder) were kept the same.

decoded = keras.layers.Dense(64, activation='relu')(encoded)

autoencoder = keras.Model(input_arr, decoded)

# This model maps an input to its encoded representation
encoder = keras.Model(input_arr, encoded)
autoencoder.compile(optimizer='adam', loss='mse')

print(autoencoder.summary())

Multi-modal models¶

In our multi-modal models the latent space is of two layers post concatenation. This is because we want to enable the NN to learn combinations of pairwise alpha carbons distances and dihedral angles which can be potentially useful for the reconstruction of the 3D protein structure.

# Multi-modal Model
input_dist = keras.Input(shape=(173755,))
encoded_dist = keras.layers.Dense(1024, activation='relu', kernel_initializer=keras.initializers.he_uniform())(input_dist)
encoded_dist = keras.layers.Dense(512, activation='relu', kernel_initializer=keras.initializers.he_uniform())(encoded_dist)
encoded_dist = keras.layers.Dense(256, activation='relu', kernel_initializer=keras.initializers.he_uniform())(encoded_dist)
encoded_dist = keras.layers.Dense(128, activation='relu', kernel_initializer=keras.initializers.he_uniform())(encoded_dist)
encoded_dist = keras.layers.Dense(64, activation='relu', kernel_initializer=keras.initializers.he_uniform())(encoded_dist)

input_dihe = keras.Input(shape=(589,))
encoded_dihe = keras.layers.Dense(512, activation='relu', kernel_initializer=keras.initializers.he_uniform())(input_dihe)
encoded_dihe = keras.layers.Dense(256, activation='relu', kernel_initializer=keras.initializers.he_uniform())(encoded_dihe)
encoded_dihe = keras.layers.Dense(128, activation='relu', kernel_initializer=keras.initializers.he_uniform())(encoded_dihe)
encoded_dihe = keras.layers.Dense(64, activation='relu', kernel_initializer=keras.initializers.he_uniform())(encoded_dihe)

x = keras.layers.Concatenate()([encoded_dist, encoded_dihe])
latent = keras.layers.Dense(128, activation='relu', kernel_initializer=keras.initializers.he_uniform(), activity_regularizer= keras.regularizers.l1(10e-5))(x)
latent = keras.layers.Dense(64, activation='relu', kernel_initializer=keras.initializers.he_uniform(), activity_regularizer= keras.regularizers.l1(10e-5))(latent)

decoded = keras.layers.Dense(64, activation='relu', kernel_initializer=keras.initializers.he_uniform())(latent)
decoded = keras.layers.Dense(128, activation='relu', kernel_initializer=keras.initializers.he_uniform())(decoded)
decoded = keras.layers.Dense(256, activation='relu', kernel_initializer=keras.initializers.he_uniform())(decoded)
decoded = keras.layers.Dense(512, activation='relu', kernel_initializer=keras.initializers.he_uniform())(decoded)
decoded = keras.layers.Dense(1024, activation='relu', kernel_initializer=keras.initializers.he_uniform())(decoded)
decoded = keras.layers.Dense(1776, activation='relu')(decoded)


# Total model
autoencoder = keras.Model(inputs=[input_dist, input_dihe], outputs=decoded)

# This model maps an input to its encoded representation
encoder = keras.Model(inputs=[input_dist, input_dihe], outputs=latent)

# Show model
print(autoencoder.summary())
plot_model(autoencoder, to_file='autoencoder_multimodal.png', show_shapes=True, show_layer_names=True)

Multi-modal models v2-3: encoders(v2) and decoders(v2 and v3) weight initialization from single-modes Networks + no dropout¶

The architecture of these models is identical to the one shown above. The main difference is the weight initializations. here we copied the weights from the single modal models. Specifically:

Model v2:¶

Only the weights for both encoders were initlialized using the trained weights from the single mode models

Model v3:¶

On top of the weights for both encoders, the weights in the decoder were initialized using the trained weights of the decoder from the best single-mode model )the one with the pairwise alpha carbon distances as shown below).

The way we transfer the weights is shown below. (The weights transfer is done before compilation)

latent = keras.layers.Dense(64, activation='relu', activity_regularizer= keras.regularizers.l1(10e-5))(latent)
latent = keras.layers.Dropout(0.2)(latent)

decoded = keras.layers.Dense(64, activation='relu')(latent)
decoded = keras.layers.Dropout(0.2)(decoded)
decoded = keras.layers.Dense(128, activation='relu')(decoded)
decoded = keras.layers.Dropout(0.2)(decoded)
decoded = keras.layers.Dense(256, activation='relu')(decoded)
decoded = keras.layers.Dropout(0.2)(decoded)
decoded = keras.layers.Dense(512, activation='relu')(decoded)
decoded = keras.layers.Dropout(0.2)(decoded)
decoded = keras.layers.Dense(1024, activation='relu')(decoded)
decoded = keras.layers.Dropout(0.2)(decoded)
decoded = keras.layers.Dense(1776, activation='relu')(decoded)

# Total model
autoencoder = keras.Model(inputs=[input_dist, input_dihe], outputs=decoded)

# This model maps an input to its encoded representation
encoder = keras.Model(inputs=[input_dist, input_dihe], outputs=latent)

#Compile
autoencoder.compile(optimizer='adam', loss='mse')

# Show model
print(autoencoder.summary())
plot_model(autoencoder, to_file='autoencoder_multimodal.png', show_shapes=True, show_layer_names=True)

As we can see the basic model does not improve the performances of the best single model. This might be due to the limit number of epochs. In fact in this model we have a greater number of weights, which might need more epochs for better results. Interestingly, when we loaded the weights of the encoders (the different modalities) we observe the worsening of the performance. When the weights of the decoder of the best single mode were used for initialization, we observe a clear improvement of the performance, and slight improvement compared to the best single model. We cannot assess however this improvement to be due to the multi-modality. Lastly, when we added dropout to all the layers, we observe a drastic improvement of the model performance, whose losses for validation and training go to a minimum of 0.04.

Additional analyses¶

In this section we are going to do some preliminary analyses on how similar the reconstructed structures to the oeriginal frames. We will start with a visual investigation to check the overall conformation is preserved and if the differences in distance between secondary structures in different frames are captured. This change of distances distances are critical for the function of this protein. After checking that the distances between secondary structures are conserved, we investigated the assignment of secondary structures themselves. Lastly we checked the latent space of our best model to investigate if the separation and overlap of the different states of the protein are meaningful.

Build 3D structure files from numpy output file¶

In [ ]:
def build_molecule(mol, name):
    f = open(name+'.xyz', 'w')
    f.write(str(len(mol))+'\n')
    f.write('reconstructed molecule \n')

    for i in mol:
        x, y, z = str(i[0]*10), str(i[1]*10), str(i[2]*10)
        f.write('C       '+x+'      '+y+'      '+z+'\n')
    f.close()
    
    print(name +' file ready')

Secondary structure assignment evaluation¶

We observed ho the spatial relation between secondary structures is kept in the reconstructure. But how well are the secondary structures preserved? We can investigate it by using a secondary structure assignment tool to see if in the predicted structure the secondary structures formed are well assigned. For this analysis we used PCASSO, a tool for the assignment of secondary structure based on alpha carbon position (the output of our model). We want to compare if the output of our model is capable to retain the secondary structure, which would demonstrate that the latent space of our model is preserving this crucial type of information. the tool is available at: https://brooks.chem.lsa.umich.edu/index.php?pcassoserver=submit

original = open('test_ss.txt', 'r')
predicted = open('best_pred_ss.txt', 'r')

for line in original:
    sp = line.split()
    original_ss = np.array(sp[1::2])[1:]

for line in predicted:
    sp = line.split()
    predicted_ss = np.array(sp[1::2])[1:]

c= 0 
divergent = []
for i in range(len(predicted_ss)):
    if predicted_ss[i] == original_ss[i]:
        c += 1
    else:
        divergent.append([original_ss[i], predicted_ss[i]])

print('Correct assignment of secondary stucture')
correct_pred_percentage = c/len(predicted_ss)*100
print(correct_pred_percentage)

# Secondary structure involvment in wrong assignment'
C, H, E = 0, 0, 0
for pair in divergent:
    for i in pair:
        if i == 'C':
            C += 1
        elif i == 'H':
            H += 1
        elif i == 'E':
            E += 1
wrong_ss = [C, H, E]

Analysis of the latent space¶

Ultimately we want to obtain a good latent space that we can project to obtain a visual conformational space of the protein. To do so we reduced the latent space obtained using UMAP. We want to check if the different states of this protein are well projected and try to rationalize potential overlaps/separation to assess the goodness of he conformational space.

From the plot above we observe that the different states of the protein are well separated for the most part. Whilst some overlapping is to be expected as different states should explore some of the same energy minima, the circular overlap are quite difficult to rationalize. To be frank while it is encouraging, more work should be done to obtain a better conformational space. The problem is defining better, which leads to... our final remarks

Final remarks¶

Although they were on the back of the structure, some atoms were misplaced in the predicted structures. We noticed that the problem strongly worsened for our single modality models. We still have to investigate if the dropout was what helped the most or the usage of multi-modalities. From the plots of the models trained so far it seems the first, but since we don;t have the data for the single-mode models with dropout we cannot exclude the latter. Another potential cause might be an error when featurizing the data. Regardless the reason, this odd placing fr this atoms in the structure might be the cause for those conformational space oddities. To be fair we used this data because it was the one Francesco was playing around, for publication we might want an easier and better characterized protein systems for an easy interpretation of, and therefore validation of quality of, the projected conformational space.

Overall, we are going to test to other systems, potentially include more features (modalities) which might help defining the conformational space, switch from qualitative to quantitative analysis (or at least include more structure in the qualitative analysis to get some statistics), and keep working in improving the architecture. On the latter, besides keep investigating the dropouts vs modalities effects discussed above, we are planning to implement another new scheme to input the alpha carbon distances information into the latent space which we would like to discuss with you in the near future!

To conclude, we managed to reconstruct a protein 3-Dimensional structure using only its geometrical features. Whilst the predicted structures were not perfect, the secondary structures, their spatial relations (tertieary structure), and the biologically relevant structural changes were all present in the predicted structure, and therefore well captured in the conformational latent space! Given the great complexity of this particular protein,( at least compared to other protein systems) all and all we are pretty impressed with the results!
